<div class="floatright"><a href="/wiki/File:Classic_BattleTech_logo_2006.png" class="image" title="Classic BattleTech logo"><img alt="Classic BattleTech logo" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/7/7c/Classic_BattleTech_logo_2006.png/335px-Classic_BattleTech_logo_2006.png" width="335" height="40" border="0" /></a></div>
<p><b>BattleTech</b> is a <a href="/wiki/Wargaming" title="Wargaming">wargaming</a> and <a href="/wiki/Science_fiction" title="Science fiction">science fiction</a> franchise, launched by <a href="/wiki/FASA_Corporation" title="FASA Corporation" class="mw-redirect">FASA Corporation</a>. In 2000, FASA properties were acquired by <a href="/wiki/WizKids" title="WizKids">WizKids</a>. WizKids in 2003 was later purchased by <a href="/wiki/Topps" title="Topps">Topps</a>, Inc. in 2003.<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> and became current owner of the property. The series began in 1984 with FASA's debut of the board game <i><a href="/wiki/Classic_BattleTech" title="Classic BattleTech">BattleTech</a></i> (originally named <i>BattleDroids</i>) by <a href="/wiki/Jordan_Weisman" title="Jordan Weisman">Jordan Weisman</a> and L. Ross Babcock III, and has since grown to include numerous expansions to the original game, several <a href="/wiki/MechWarrior_(video_games)" title="MechWarrior (video games)" class="mw-redirect">computer and video games</a>, a <a href="/wiki/Collectible_card_game" title="Collectible card game">collectible card game</a>, a series of more than 100 <a href="/wiki/Novels" title="Novels" class="mw-redirect">novels</a>, an animated <a href="/wiki/Television_program" title="Television program">television series</a> and more.<sup id="cite_ref-HG_1-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-HG-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
